[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1900 Summer Olympics, now officially known as the Games of the II Olympiad, were an international multi-sport event held in Paris, France, from May 14 to October 28, 1900, as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] A total of 1,226 athletes representing 26 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The games featured 95 events in 19 sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Archery, Basque pelota, cricket, croquet, equestrian jumping, football, golf, polo, rugby union, rowing, sailing, tug of war, and water polo were contested for the first time at these Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Women competed in the Olympics for the first time during the 1900 games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Athletes representing 19 NOCs received at least one medal.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] France won the most of every type of medal, while the United States won the second-most of every type of medal.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Spain, Cuba, the Netherlands, Italy, and Belgium all won their nation's first Olympic gold medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Belgium, Italy, Netherlands, Cuba, Spain, Norway, India, Bohemia, and Sweden all won their nation's first Olympic medals of any kind.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] In the early Olympic Games, several team events were contested by athletes from multiple nations.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] During the 1900 games, athletes participating in mixed teams won medals in football, polo, rowing, tennis, and tug of war.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Gilt silver medals were awarded for first place in shooting, lifesaving, motor racing, and gymnastics, while second place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, sailing, tennis, gymnastics, fencing, equestrian, and athletics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Third place bronze medals were awarded in gymnastics, firefighting, and shooting.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] However, in many sports, medals were not awarded, with most of the listed prizes being cups and other similar trophies.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver, and bronze medals to competitors who earned first, second, and third place finishes in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Alvin Kraenzlein won four gold medals at the 1900 Summer Olympics, the most of any competing athlete.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Prizes worth a total of 953,448 francs were awarded to the athletes across the competitions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Various cash prizes and art objects were awarded to the athletes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] In addition, medals and plaques were distributed, including the sports plaque designed by Frédéric de Vernon, available in gilt silver, silver, or bronze.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Produced by Monnaie de Paris, the medal features two sides.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] On the front, a winged goddess holds laurel branches high above her head, with Paris and the grand monuments of the Universal Exhibition visible in the background.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] On the reverse, a victorious athlete stands proudly on a podium, raising a laurel branch in his right hand.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Behind him, a stadium and the Acropolis of Athens serve as a reminder of the deep connection between ancient and modern Olympic traditions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The medal table is based on information provided by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and is consistent with IOC conventional sorting in its published medal tables.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The table uses the Olympic medal table sorting method.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won, where a nation is an entity represented by a NOC.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] If teams are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by their IOC country code.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was the sixth of ten major expositions held in the city between 1855 and 1937.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was held at the esplanade of Les Invalides, the Champ de Mars, the Trocadéro and at the banks of the Seine between them, with an additional section in the Bois de Vincennes, and it was visited by more than fifty million people.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Many international congresses and other events were held within the framework of the exposition, including the 1900 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It also brought international attention to the Art Nouveau style.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Additionally, it showcased France as a major colonial power through numerous pavilions built on the hill of the Trocadéro Palace.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The first international exposition was held in London in 1851.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The French Emperor Napoleon III attended and was deeply impressed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] He commissioned the first Paris Universal Exposition of 1855.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Its purpose was to promote French commerce, technology and culture.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was followed by another in 1867, and, after the Emperor's downfall in 1870, another in 1878, celebrating national unity after the defeat of the Paris Commune, and then in 1889, celebrating the centennial of the French Revolution.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Planning for the 1900 Exposition began in 1892, under President Carnot, with Alfred Picard as Commissioner-General.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Three French Presidents and ten Ministers of Commerce held office before it was completed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] President Carnot died shortly before it was completed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Though many of the buildings were not finished, the exposition was opened on 14 April 1900 by President Émile Loubet.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Countries from around the world were invited by France to showcase their achievements and cultures.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Of the fifty-six countries invited to participate with official representation, forty accepted, plus an additional number of colonies and protectorates of France, the Netherlands, Great Britain, and Portugal.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Austria, Bosnia-Herzegovina and Hungary participated as independent nations, although belonging to Austria-Hungary at that time.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Finland, although having a national pavilion located at the Rue des Nations, officially participated as part of Russia.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Egypt, also with an own pavilion, participated as part of Turkey.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The few exhibitors from countries without an official presence at the fair participated under a joint "International Section".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The site of the exposition covered 112 hectares (280 acres) along the left and right banks of the Seine from the esplanade of Les Invalides to the Eiffel Tower (built for the 1889 Exposition) at the Champ de Mars.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It also included the Grand Palais and Petit Palais on the right bank.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] An additional section of 104 hectares (260 acres) for agricultural exhibits and other structures was built in the Bois de Vincennes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The total area of the exposition, 216 hectares (530 acres), was ten times larger than the 1855 Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The exposition buildings were meant to be temporary; they were built on iron frames covered with plaster and staff, a kind of inexpensive artificial stone.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Many of the buildings were unfinished when the exposition opened, and most were demolished immediately after it closed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Porte Monumentale de Paris, located on the Place de la Concorde, was the main entrance of the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The architect of the monument overall was René Binet, although many others contributed to the constituent parts.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] His overall design was inspired by the biological studies of Ernst Haeckel.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was composed of towering polychrome ceramic decoration in Byzantine motifs, crowned by a statue 6.5 metres (21 ft) high called *La Parisienne*.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Unlike classical statues, she was dressed in modern Paris fashion.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] *La Parisienne* was executed by sculptor Paul Moreau-Vauthier who collaborated with Paris' pre-eminiment haute couturier of the day, Jeanne Paquin, who designed the figure's fashionable attire.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Below the statue was a sculptural prow of a boat, the symbol of Paris, and friezes depicting the workers who built the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The central arch was flanked by two slender, candle-like towers, resembling triumph columns.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The gateway was brightly illuminated at night by 3,200 light bulbs and an additional forty arc lamps.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Forty thousand visitors an hour could pass beneath the arch to approach the twenty-six ticket booths.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Above the ticket booth windows, the names of provincial cities were inscribed, symbolically enacting a hierarchical relation between Paris and the provinces.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The structure of the entrance tower as a whole was adorned with Byzantine motifs and Persian ceramic ornamentation, but the true inspiration behind the piece was not of cultural background.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Binet sought inspiration from science, tucking the vertebrae of a dinosaur, the cells of a beehive, rams, peacocks, and poppies into the design alongside other animalistic stimuli.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Gateway, like the exposition buildings, was intended to be temporary, and was demolished as soon as the exposition was finished.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The ceramic frieze depicting the workers of the exposition was designed by Anatole Guillot, an academic sculptor.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The workers frieze was preserved by the head of the ceramics firm that made it, Émile Müller, and moved to what is now Parc Müller in the town of Breuillet, Essonne.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The workers were situated above a frieze of animals designed by sculptor Paul Jouve and executed by ceramicist Alexandre Bigot.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Pont Alexandre III was an essential link of the exposition, connecting the pavilions and palaces on the left and right banks of the Seine.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was named after Czar Alexander III of Russia, who had died in 1894, and celebrated the recent alliance between France and Russia.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The foundation stone was laid by his son, Czar Nicholas II in 1896, and the bridge was finished in 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was the work of engineers Jean Resal and Amédée D'Alby and architect Gaston Cousin.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The widest and longest of the Paris bridges at the time, it was constructed on a single arch of steel 108 metres (354 ft) long.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Though it was named after the Russian Czar, the themes of the decoration were almost entirely French.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] At the ends, the bridge was supported by four massive stone pylons 13 metres (43 ft) high, decorated with statues of the *Renomées* (The Renowned), female figures with trumpets, and gilded statues of the horse Pegasus.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] At the base of the pedestals are allegorical statues representing the France of Charlemagne, the France of the Renaissance, the France of Louis XIV and France in 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Russian element was in the center, with statuary of the Nymphs of the Neva River holding a gilded seal of the Russian Empire.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] At the same time that the Pont Alexander III was built, a similar bridge, the Trinity Bridge was built in Saint-Petersburg, and was dedicated to French-Russian friendship by French President Félix Faure.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] To house the industrial, commercial, scientific, technological and cultural exhibitions, the French organization built huge thematic pavilions on the esplanade of Les Invalides and the Champ de Mars and reused the Galerie des machines from the 1889 Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] On the other bank of the Seine, they built the Grand Palais and the Petit Palais for the fine arts exhibitions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The 83,047 French and foreign exhibitors at the fair were divided into eighteen groups based on their subject matter, which in turn were divided into 121 classes, and based on the class to which they belonged, they were allocated in the corresponding official thematic pavilion.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Each thematic pavilion was divided into national sections, which were the responsibility of the corresponding country and where its exhibitors were located.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Some country with a strong presence in a specific sector, at its own request, was even granted a plot adjoining to the main building to build a small pavilion to house its exhibitors.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Twenty-one of the thirty-three official pavilions were devoted to technology and the sciences.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Among the most popular was the Palace of Optics, whose main attractions included the Great Paris Exposition Telescope, which enlarged the image of the moon ten thousand times.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The image was projected on a screen 144 square metres (1,550 sq ft) in size, in a hall which seated two thousand visitors.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] This telescope was the largest refracting telescope at that time.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The optical tube assembly was 60 metres (200 ft) long and 1.5 metres (4 ft 11 in) in diameter, and was fixed in place due to its mass.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Light from the sky was sent into the tube by a movable 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) mirror.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Another very popular feature of the Palace of Optics was the giant kaleidoscope, which attracted three million visitors.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Other features of the optics pavilion included demonstrations of X-rays and dancers performing in phosphorescent costumes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Palais des Illusions (Palace of Illusions), adjoining the Palace of Optics, was an extremely popular exhibition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was a large hall which used mirrors and electric lighting to create a show of colorful and bizarre optical illusions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was preserved after the exposition in the Musée Grévin.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Another scientific attraction was the aquarium, the largest in the world at the time, viewed from an underground gallery 722 metres (2,369 ft) long.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The water tanks were each 38 metres (125 ft) long, 18 metres (59 ft) wide and 6.5 metres (21 ft) deep, and contained a wide selection of exotic marine life.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Palace of Electricity and the adjoining Water Castle (*Chateau d'Eau*), designed by architects Eugène Hénard and Edmond Paulin, were among the most popular sights.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Palace of Electricity was built partly incorporating architectural elements of the old Palace of the Champ de Mars from the 1889 Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Palace was enormous, 420 metres (1,380 ft) long and 60 metres (200 ft) wide, and its form suggested a giant peacock spreading its tail.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The central tower was crowned by an enormous illuminated star and a chariot carrying a statue of the Spirit of Electricity 6.5 metres (21 ft) high, holding aloft a torch powered by 50,000 volts of electricity, provided by the steam engines and generators inside the Palace.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Electrical lighting was used extensively to keep the fair open well into the night.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Producing the light for the exposition consumed 200,000 kilograms (440,000 lb) of oil an hour.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The facade of the Palace and the Water Castle, across from it, were lit by an additional 7,200 incandescent lamps and seventeen arc lamps.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Visitors could go inside to see the steam-powered generators which provided electricity for the buildings of the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Water castle, facing the Palace of Electricity, had an equally imposing appearance.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It had two large domes, between which was a gigantic fountain, circulating 100,000 litres (22,000 imp gal; 26,000 US gal) of water a minute.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Thanks to the power from Palace of Electricity, the fountain was illuminated at night by continually changing colored lights.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Grand Palais, officially the *Grand Palais des beaux-arts et des arts decoratifs*, was built on the right bank upon the site of the Palace of Industry of the 1855 Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was the work of two architects, Henri Deglane for the main body of the building, and Albert Thomas for the west wing, or Palais d'Antin.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The iron frame of the Grand Palais was quite modern for its time; it appeared light, but in fact, it used 9,000 tonnes (8,900 long tons; 9,900 short tons) of metal, compared with seven thousand for the construction of the Eiffel Tower.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The facade was in the ornate Beaux-Arts style or Neo-Baroque style.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The more modern interior iron framework, huge skylights and stairways offered decorative elements in the new Art Nouveau style, particularly in the railings of the staircase, which were intricately woven in fluid, organic forms.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] During the fair, the interior served as the setting for the exhibitions of paintings and sculptures.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The main body of the Grand Palais housed the *Exposition décennale des beaux-arts de 1889 à 1900* with the paintings of French artists in the north wing, the paintings of artists from other countries in the south wing and the sculptures in the central hall, with some outdoor sculptures nearby.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Palais d'Antin, or west wing, housed the *Exposition centennale de l'art français de 1800 à 1889*.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Petit Palais, that is facing the Grand Palais, was designed by Charles Girault.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Much like the Grand Palais, the facade is Beaux-Arts and Neo-Baroque, reminiscent of the Grand Trianon and the stable at Chantilly.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The interior offers examples of Art Nouveau, particularly in the railings of the curving stairways, the tiles of the floors, the stained glass, and the murals on the ceiling of the arcade around the garden.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The entrance murals were painted by Paul-Albert Besnard and Paul Albert Laurens.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] During the fair, the Petit Palais housed the *Exposition rétrospective de l'art français des origines à 1800*.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The industrial and commercial exhibits were located inside several large palaces on the esplanade between les Invalides and the Alexander III Bridge.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] One of the largest and most ornate was the Palais des Manufactures Nationale, whose facade included a colorful ceramic gateway, designed by sculptor Jules Coutan and architect Charles Risler and made by the Sèvres Porcelain manufactory.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] After the exposition it was moved to the wall of Square Felix-Déésroulles, next to the Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Prés, where it can be seen today.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Palace of Furniture and Decoration was particularly lavish and presented many displays of the new Art Nouveau style.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Palace of Agriculture and Food was inside the former Galerie des machines, an enormous iron-framed building from the 1889 Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Its most popular feature was the Champagne Palace, offering displays and samples of French Champagne.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Fifty-six countries were invited to the exposition, and forty accepted.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Rue des Nations was created along the banks of the Seine between the esplanade of Les Invalides and the Champ de Mars for the national pavilions of the larger countries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilions were all temporary, made of plaster and *staff* on a metal frame and were designed in an architectural style that represented a period in the country's history, often imitating famous national monuments.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Behind them, in second line, were located the pavilions of Denmark, Portugal, Peru, Persia, Finland, Luxembourg, Bulgaria and Romania.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The other nations were located elsewhere in the exposition site.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] In addition to their own national pavilion, the countries managed other spaces at the fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The industrial, commercial, scientific and cultural exhibitors of each country were distributed among the national sections of the different official thematic pavilions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilion of Turkey was designed by a French architect, Adrien-René Dubuisson, and was a mixture of copies of Islamic architecture from mosques in Istanbul and elsewhere in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Turkey managed 4,000 square metres (43,000 sq ft) of exhibition space at the fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The United States pavilion was modest, a variation on the United States Capitol Building designed by Charles Allerton Coolidge and Georges Morin-Goustiaux.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The main U.S. presence was in the commercial and industrial palaces.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] One unusual aspect of the U.S. presence was The Exhibit of American Negroes at the Palace of Social Economy, a joint project of Daniel Murray, the Assistant Librarian of Congress, Thomas J.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Calloway, a lawyer and the primary organizer of the exhibit, and W.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The goal of the exhibition was to demonstrate progress and commemorate the lives of African Americans at the transition of the 19th into the 20th century.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilions of the Austro-Hungarian domains in the Balkans, Bosnia and Herzegovina, offered displays on their lifestyles, consisting of folklore traditions, highlighting peasanthood and the embroidery goods produced in the country.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Designed by Karl Panek, it featured murals on the history of Slavic peoples by Alphonse Mucha.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilion of Hungary was designed by Zoltán Bálint and Lajos Jámbor.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Its cupola displayed agricultural produce and hunting equipment.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The British Royal pavilion consisted of a mock-Jacobean mansion designed by Sir Edwin Lutyens that was decorated with pictures and furniture.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The furnishings designed by Nellie Whichelo included hangings that were more than 12 by 13 feet (3.7 by 4.0 m), which had taken 56 ladies six weeks to embroider.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilion was largely used for receptions for important visitors to the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The German pavilion was the tallest, at 76 metres (249 ft), designed by Johannes Radke and built of wood and stained glass.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] However, most of the German presence at the exposition was in the commercial pavilions, where they had important displays of German technology and machinery, as well as models of German steamships and a full-scale model of a German lighthouse.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Royal Pavilion of Spain was designed in Neo-Plateresque style by José Urioste Velada.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It housed the Retrospective Exhibition of Spanish Art formed by the collection of tapestries, in which thirty-seven pieces made between the 15th and 18th centuries from the Royal Collections were exhibited.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilion basement housed a Spanish-themed café-restaurant, named *La Feria*, that was the first restaurant in History with a completely electric kitchen.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Sweden's yellow and red structure covered in pine shingles drew attention with its bright colours.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Serbia presented itself with a 550 square metres (5,900 sq ft) pavilion resembling a church, in the Serbo-Byzantine style whose main architect was Milan Kapetanović from Belgrade, in cooperation with architect Milorad Ruvidić.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Serbia presented numerous products at the exposition, such as wine, food, fabrics, minerals and won a total of 19 gold, 69 silver and 98 bronze medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Some of the Serbian fine art on display were the painting *The Proclamation of Dušan's Law Codex* by Paja Jovanović and *Monument to heroes of Kosovo* by Đorđe Jovanović, which stands today in Kruševac.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilion of Finland, designed by Gesellius, Lindgren, Saarinen, had clean-cut, modern architecture.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Russia had an imposing presence on the Trocadéro hill.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Russian pavilion, designed by Robert Meltzer, was inspired by the towers of the Kremlin and had exhibits and architecture presenting artistic treasures from Samarkand, Bukhara and other Russian dependencies in Central Asia.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Chinese pavilion, designed by Louis Masson-Détourbet, was in the form of a Buddhist temple with staff in Chinese traditional dress.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] This pavilion suffered some disruption in August 1900, when anti-Western rebels seized the International delegations in Beijing in the Boxer Rebellion and held them for several weeks until an expeditionary force from the Eight-Nation Alliance arrived and recaptured the city.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] During the disruption at the fair, a Chinese procession was attacked by angered Parisians.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Korean pavilion, designed by Eugène Ferret, was modelled after Geunjeongjeon hall in the royal palace.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was mostly stocked by French Oriental collectors, including Victor Collin de Plancy, with a supplement of Korean goods from Korea.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] One object of note on display was the *Jikji*, the oldest extant book printed with movable metal type.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Morocco had its pavilion near the Eiffel Tower and was designed by Henri-Jules Saladin.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] An area of several dozen hectares on the hill of the Trocadéro Palace was set aside for the pavilions of the colonies and protectorates of France, the Netherlands, Great Britain, and Portugal.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The largest space was for the French colonies in Africa, the Caribbean, the Pacific and Southeast Asia.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] These pavilions featured traditional architecture of the countries and displays of local products mixed with modern electric lighting, motion pictures, dioramas, and guides, soldiers, and musicians in local costumes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The French Caribbean islands promoted their rum and other products, while the French colony of New Caledonia highlighted its exotic varieties of wood and its rich mineral deposits.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The North African French colonies were especially present; The Tunisian pavilion was a miniature recreation of the Sidi Mahrez Mosque of Tunis.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Algeria, Sudan, Dahomey, Guinea and the other French African colonies presented pavilions based on their traditional religious architecture and marketplaces, with guides in costume.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The French colonies of Indochina, Tonkin and Cambodia also had an impressive presence, with recreations of pagodas and palaces, musicians and dancers, and a recreation of a riverside village from Laos.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Netherlands displayed the exotic culture of its crown colony, the Dutch East Indies.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pavilion displayed a faithful reconstruction of 8th-century Sari temple and also Indonesian vernacular architecture of Rumah Gadang from Minangkabau, West Sumatra.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Besides its official scientific, industrial and artistic palaces, the exposition offered an extraordinary variety of attractions, amusements and diversions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Eiffel Tower, which was built as the main entrance of the 1889 Exposition, was the main and central attraction of the 1900 Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] For this exposition, it was repainted in shaded tones from yellow-orange at the base to light yellow at the top and was fitted with 7,000 electric lamps.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] At the same time, the lifts in the east and west legs were replaced by lifts running as far as the second level and the lift in the north pillar was removed and replaced by a staircase to the first level.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The layout of both first and second levels was modified, with the space available for visitors on the second level.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The *Grande Roue de Paris* was a very popular attraction.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was a gigantic ferris wheel 110 metres (360 ft) high, which took its name from a similar wheel created by George Washington Gale Ferris Jr. at the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It could carry 1,600 passengers in its forty cars in a single voyage.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The cost of a ride was one franc for a second class car, and two francs for a more spacious first-class car.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Despite the high price, passengers often had to wait an hour for a place.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Street of the future) moving sidewalk was a very popular and useful attraction, given the large size of the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It ran along the edge of the exposition, from the esplanade of Les Invalides to the Champ de Mars, passing through nine stations along the way, where passengers could board.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The fare was an average of fifty centimes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The sidewalk was accessed from a platform 7 metres (23 ft) above the ground level.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The passengers stepped from the platform onto the moving sidewalk traveling at 4.2 kilometres per hour (2.6 mph), then onto a more rapid sidewalk moving at 8.5 kilometres per hour (5.3 mph).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The sidewalks had posts with handles which passengers could hold onto, or they could walk.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was designed by architect Joseph Lyman Silsbee and engineer Max E.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] A Decauville electric train followed the same route, running at an average speed of 17 kilometres per hour (11 mph) in the opposite direction of the moving sidewalk.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The rail track was sometimes at 7 metres (23 ft) high like the movable sidewalks, sometimes at ground level and sometimes underground.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] An experimental passenger electrobus line, designed by Louis Lombard-Gérin, ran in the Bois de Vincennes from 2 August to 12 November 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was a 2.5 kilometres (1.6 mi) long circular route connecting the recently opened Porte de Vincennes metro station with Lac Daumesnil.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was the first trolleybus in regular passenger service in History.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The *Globe Céleste* was an immense globe-shaped planetarium which offered a presentation on the night sky.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The globe, designed by Napoléon de Tédesco, was 45 metres (148 ft) in diameter, and the blue and gold exterior was painted with the constellations and the signs of the zodiac.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was placed atop a masonry support 18 metres (59 ft) high, supported by four columns.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] A flower garden on the support surrounded the globe.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Spectators seated in armchairs inside watched a presentation on the stars and planets projected overhead.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The sphere was the scene of a fatal accident on 29 April 1900 when one of its access ramps, hastily made of a newly introduced material, reinforced concrete, collapsed onto the street below, killing nine people.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Following the accident the French government established the first regulations for the use of reinforced concrete.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Lumière brothers, who had made the first public projections of a motion picture in 1895, presented their films on a colossal screen, 21 metres (69 ft) by 16 metres (52 ft), in the Gallery of Machines.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Another innovation in motion pictures was presented at the exposition at the Phono-Cinema Theater; a primitive talking motion picture, where the image on the screen was synchronized to the sound from phonographs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] An even more ambitious experiment in motion pictures was the *Cinéorama* of Raoul Grimoin Sanson, which simulated a voyage in a balloon.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The film, projected on a circular screen 93 metres (305 ft) in circumference by ten synchronized projectors, depicted a landscape passing below.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The spectators sat in the center above the projectors, in what resembled the basket suspended beneath a large balloon.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Another popular attraction was the *Mareorama*, which simulated a voyage by ship from Villefranche to Constantinople.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The viewers stood on the railing of a ship simulator, watching painted images pass by of the cities and seascapes en route.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The illusion was aided by machinery that rocked the ship, and fans which blew gusts of wind.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The Swiss Village, at the edge of the exposition near Avenue de Sufren and Motte-Piquet, was a recreation of a Swiss mountainside village, complete with a 35 metres (115 ft) cascade, a lake and collection of thirty-five chalets.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The *Panorama du Tour du Monde* was an animated panorama journey from Europe to Japan in a building by Alexandre Marcel in the architectural styles of India, China, Cambodia, Japan and Renaissance Europe.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It consisted in panoramic paintings by Louis Dumoulin in front of which groups of native people, dressed accordingly, move, play, dance, stroll or work.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The visitor traveled through representations of Fuenterrabía (Spain), the Pnyx hill in Athens (Greece), the cemetery of Stamboul and the Golden Horn of Constantinople (Turkey), Syria, the Suez Canal (Egypt), Ceylon, the Angkor Wat temple (Cambodia), Shanghai (China) and Nikkō (Japan).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The visit continued by showing dioramas of Rome, Moscow, New York and Amsterdam and ended with a mobile panorama of a boat trip along the coast of Provence, from Marseille to La Ciotat.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] It was funded and sponsored by the *Compagnie des messageries maritimes*.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Other recreations with costumed vendors and musicians elsewhere the exposition included recreations of the bazaars, souks and street markets of Algiers, Tunis and Laos, a Venetian canal with gondolas, a Russian village and a Japanese tea house.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The exposition had several large theatres and music halls, the largest of which was the Palais des Fêtes, which had fifteen thousand seats, and offered programs of music, ballet, historical recreations and diverse spectacles.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Other diversions elsewhere in and around the exposition included an orchestra from Madagascar, a Comedy Theater, and the Columbia Theater at Port Maillot, with acts ranging from panoramas of life in the Orient to a water ballet.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] These diversions were popular but expensive; entry to the Comedy Theater cost up to five francs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The most celebrated actress during the exposition was Sarah Bernhardt, who had her own theater, The Théâtre Sarah Bernhardt (now the Théâtre de la Ville), and premiered one of her most famous roles during the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] This was *L'Aiglon*, a new play by Edmond Rostand in which she played the Duc de Reichstadt, the son of Napoleon Bonaparte, imprisoned by his unloving mother and family until his melancholy death in the Schönbrunn Palace in Vienna.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The play ended with a memorable death scene; according to one critic, she died "as dying angels would die if they were allowed to." The play ran for nearly a year, with standing-room places selling for as much as 600 gold francs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Another popular diversion during the exposition was the theater of the American dancer, Loie Fuller, who performed a famous Serpentine dance in which she waved large silk scarves which seemed to envelop her into a cloud.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Her performance was widely reproduced in photographs, paintings and drawings by Art Nouveau artists and sculptors, and were captured in very early motion pictures.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] She was filmed on ten 70mm projectors that created a 330-degree picture, patented by Cinéorama.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] A large area within the Bois de Vincennes was set aside for sporting events, which included, among others, many of the events of the 1900 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The 1900 Summer Olympics were the second modern Olympics games held, and the first ones held outside Greece.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Between 14 May and 28 October 1900, an enormous number of sporting activities were held along the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The sporting events rarely used the term of "Olympic".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Indeed, the term "Olympic Games" was replaced by "*Concours internationaux d'exercices physiques et de sport*" (transl.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] "International physical exercises and sports competition") in the official report of the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The International Olympic Committee (IOC) had no real control over the organization, no official interpretation has ever been made and various sources list differing events, further adding to the confusion that was Paris 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] According to the IOC, 997 competitors took part in nineteen different sports, including women competing for the first time.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] A number of events were held for the first and only time in Olympic history, including automobile and motorcycle racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, a 200 metres (660 ft) swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] France provided 72 percent of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The United States athletes won the second largest number, with just 75 of the 997 athletes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The pigeon race was won by a bird that flew from Paris to its home in Lyon in four and a half hours.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The free balloon competition race was won by a balloon which travelled 1,925 kilometres (1,196 mi) from Paris to Russia in 35 hours and 45 minutes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Another special event at the exposition was a gigantic banquet hosted by the French President, Émile Loubet, for 20,777 mayors of France, Algeria and towns in French colonies, hosted on 22 September 1900 in the Tuileries Gardens, inside two enormous tents.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The dinner was prepared in eleven kitchens and served to 606 tables, with the orders and needs of each table supervised by telephone and vehicle.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The organizers of the exposition were not miserly in recognizing the 83,047 exhibitors of products, about half of whom came from France, and 7,161 from the United States.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The awards ceremony was held on 18 August 1900, and was attended by 11,500 persons.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] 3,156 grand prizes were handed out, 8,889 gold medals, 13,300 silver medals, 12,108 bronze medals, and 8,422 honorable mentions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Many of the participants, such as Campbell's Soup or Michigan Stove Company, added the Paris award to the advertisements and labels of their products.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The cost of an admission ticket was one franc.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] At the time, the average hourly wage for Paris workers was between forty and fifty centimes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] In addition, most popular attractions charged an admission fee, usually between fifty centimes and a franc.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The average cost of a simple meal at the exposition was 2.50 francs, the half-day wages of a worker.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The amount budgeted for the Paris Exposition was one hundred million francs; twenty million from the French government, twenty million from Paris, and the remaining sixty million expected to come from admissions, and backed by French banks and financial institutions.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The official final cost was 119 million francs, while the total amount actually collected from admission fees was 126 million francs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] However, there were unplanned expenses of twenty-two million francs for the French State, and six million francs for the City of Paris, bringing the total cost to 147 million francs, or a deficit of twenty-one million francs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The exposition was so expensive to organize and run that the cost per visitor ended up being about six hundred francs more than the price of admission.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The exhibition lost a grand total of 82,000 francs after six months in operation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Many Parisians had invested money in bonds sold to raise money for the event and therefore lost their investment.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] With a much larger than expected turnout the exhibit sites had gone up in value.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] Continuing to pay rent for the sites became increasingly hard for concessionaires as they were receiving fewer customers than anticipated.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] The concessionaires then went on strike, which ultimately resulted in the closure of a large part of the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p01] To resolve the matter, the concessionaires were given a fractional refund of the rent they had paid.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The Art Nouveau ("New Art") style, taking its name from S.Bing's store L'Art Nouveau, began to appear in Belgium and France in the 1890s and became fashionable in Europe and the United States.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] It was highly decorative and took its inspiration from the natural world, particularly from the curving lines of plants and flowers and other vegetal forms.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The architecture of the exposition was largely of the Belle Epoque style and Beaux-Arts style, or of eclectic national styles.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The store L'Art Nouveau presented a small pavilion at the exposition showcasing furniture and interior design in the new style.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Art Nouveau style decoration appeared in the interiors and decoration of many of the other buildings, notably the interior ironwork and decoration of the Monumental gateway of the exposition, the Grand Palais and the Petit Palais, and in the portal of the Palace of National Industries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The Art Nouveau style was very popular in the pavilions of decorative arts.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The jewelry firm of Fouquet and the glass and crystal manufactory of Lalique all presented collections of Art Nouveau objects.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The Sèvres Porcelain Manufactory created a series of monumental swan vases for the exposition, as well as the monumental entrance to the Palace of National Manufacturers.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Many exposition posters also made use of the Art Nouveau style.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The work of the most famous Art Nouveau poster artist, Alfons Mucha, had many forms at the exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] He designed the posters for the official Austrian participation in the exposition, painting murals depicting scenes from the history of Bosnia as well as the menu for the restaurant at the Bosnian pavilion, and designed the menu for the official opening banquet.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] He produced displays for the jeweler Georges Fouquet and the perfume maker Houbigant, with statuettes and panels of women depicting the scents of rose, orange blossom, violet and buttercup.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] His more serious art works, including his drawings for *Le Pater*, were shown in the Austrian pavilion and in the Austrian section of the Grand Palais.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Some of his murals can be seen now in the Petit Palais.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The most famous appearance was in the entrances of the stations of the Paris Métro designed by Hector Guimard.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] It also appeared in the interior decoration of many popular restaurants, notably the Pavillon Bleu at the exposition, Maxim's, and the Le Train Bleu restaurant of the Gare de Lyon, and in the portal of the Palace of National Manufacturers made by the Sèvres Porcelain Manufactory.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The exposition was a showcase not only of French Art Nouveau, but also the variations that had appeared in other parts of Europe, including the furniture of the Belgian architect and designer Victor Horta, designs of the German Jugendstil by Bruno Möhring, and of the Vienna Secession of Otto Wagner.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Their display at the exposition brought the new style international attention.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Most of the palaces and buildings constructed for the Exposition Universelle were demolished after the conclusion of the exposition and all items and materials that could be salvaged were sold or recycled.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] They were built largely of wood and covered with staff, which was formed into columns, statuary, walls, stairs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] A few of the major structures built for the exposition were preserved, including the Grand Palais and the Petit Palais, and the two major bridges, the Pont Alexandre III and the Passerelle Debilly, though the latter was later dismantled and moved a few dozen meters from its original placement.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The Compagnie du chemin de fer métropolitain de Paris (CMP) installed a total of 141 of the Art Nouveau metro station entrances designed by Hector Guimard –with and without canopy– between 1900 and 1913.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] In 1978, the 86 entrances that still existed were protected as historical monuments and have been preserved to this day, including two original canopied ones: at Porte Dauphine, on its original site and with the wall panels, and at Abbesses (moved from Hôtel de Ville in 1974).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] A third canopied entrance at Châtelet is a 2000 recreation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] None of the three pavilion-type entrances designed by Guimard have survived.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The monumental portal of the Palace of National Manufacturers, made by the Sèvres Manufactory, was preserved and moved to Square Felix-Desruelles, next to the Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Prés.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] A 2.87 metres (9 ft 5 in) copy of the Statue of Liberty by Frédéric Auguste Bartholdi exhibited at the fair, was placed in the Luxembourg Gardens in 1905 at the request of his widow.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] After visiting the *Panorama du Tour du Monde*, King Leopold II of Belgium commissioned the architect of the building, Alexandre Marcel, to build a Japanese tower and a Chinese pavilion in the Royal Domain of Laeken, Brussels, Belgium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Marcel rebuilt there the Japanese red pagoda of the *Panorama du Tour du Monde* (now known as the Japanese Tower) and moved there the original entry pavilion to the tower from Paris.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] He also built the Chinese Pavilion whose wooden panelling was sculpted in Shanghai.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Both structures are now part of the Museums of the Far East.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] One of the most curious vestiges is La Ruche, at 2 Passage de Dantzig (15th arrondissement).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] This is a three-story building constructed entirely out of bits and pieces of exposition buildings, purchased at auctions by sculptor Alfred Boucher.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The iron roof, made by Gustave Eiffel, originally covered the kiosk of the Wines of Médoc, in the palace of agriculture and foods.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The statues of women in theatrical costumes by the front door came from the Indochina pavilion, while the ornamental iron gate at the entrance was part of the Palace of Women.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] In the years after the exposition, La Ruche served as the temporary studio and home of dozens of young artists and writers including Marc Chagall, Henri Matisse, Amedeo Modigliani, Fernand Léger and the poet Guillaume Apollinaire.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] It was threatened with demolition in the 1960s but was saved by culture minister André Malraux.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The exposition had numerous critics from different points of view.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Response to the monumental gateway was mixed, with some critics comparing it to a pot-bellied stove.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] It was described as "lacking in taste" and was considered by some critics to be the ugliest of all the exhibits.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] *La Parisienne*, made by Moreau-Vauthier, was referred to by some as "the triumph of prostitution" because of her flowing robe and modernized figure and was criticized by many visitors.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The interior of the central dome had niches holding large sculptures.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] One was described as both a personification of electricity and as Salammbô, Gustave Flaubert's infamous Carthaginian *femme fatale*, who was a symbol of light.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] La Porte Monumentale is considered to be a structure of the Salammbô style and 'the most typically 1900 monument of the entire exhibition'.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The controversial gateway became known as *La Salamanda* among the public because it resembled the stocky and intricately designed salamander-stoves of the time, only adding to its ridicule.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] The chapter is considered to be an early iteration of the conversations about technology and life that continued in the 20th and 21st centuries.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1900-world-s-fair-p02] Short silent actuality films documenting the exposition by French director Georges Méliès and by Edison Manufacturing Company producer James H.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:1900-summer-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
